Dear 4:2:2 profile conformance bitstream exchange AHG members,

This is the long version of 4:2:2 profile test bitstream ID 14.  This sequence
contains field structured pictures where all the B pictures consist of 100%
bidirectional 16x8 motion compensated macroblocks.  The purpose is to stress
the decoder-under-test's memory bandwidth used for motion compensation.

The parameters for the sequence are as follows:

Sequence:	29.97Hz, "Mobile & Calendar", 125 frames
GOP:		i/p b/b b/b b/b b/b b/b p/p ...
Bitrate: 	50 Mbits/sec
Picture size:	720 x 512
Quant. scale:	Non-uniform (q_scale_type 1)
Picture struct:	Field
Extras:		Sequence display extension,
		Quantizer Matrix extension with 3 matrices
		Lausanne slice extra information byte,
		Intra DC precision of 11 bits.

The format of the picture data is:

	4:2:2 frame ("display" order) 8 bit samples per compenent.

	width  = 720
	height = 512


                   <--------width--------->
                  +------------------------+
                  |                        |      ^
                  |                        |      |
                  |                        |      |
                  |                        |      |
                  |     Luminance Pels     |    height
                  |                        |      |
                  |                        |      |
                  |                        |      V
                  +-----------+------------+
                  |           |      ^
                  |           |      |
                  |           |      |
                  |  Cb pels  |    height
                  |           |      |
                  |           |      |
                  |           |      V
                  +-----------+      -
                  |           |      ^
                  |           |      |
                  |           |      |
                  |  Cr pels  |    height
                  |           |      |
                  |           |      |
                  |           |      V
                  +-----------+      -
                   <-width/2->

Please email me with the results of your decoding -- also let me know if you
find any errors in this bitstream.

